stable, universal, or static. The essays here confirm the interests and priorities of Western Canadian scholarship that have emerged over the past forty years and remind us of the importance of Indigenous peoples, dispossession, and colonialism; of migration, race and ethnicity; of gender and women’s experiences; of the impact of the natural and built environment; and the impact of politics and the state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh  aagriculture.  aemigration.  afirst nations.  ahomestead.  aliterature.  aprairie.  aproperty rights.1 aAlison, Calder, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBret, Nickels, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChadya, Joyce M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElspeth, Tulloch, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmma, Larocque, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoster, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeather, Stanley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Esyllt W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Esyllt W., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLindy, Ledohowski, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLisa, Chilton, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarshall, Alison R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorton, Leah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorton, Leah, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNettelbeck, Amanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g